#!/usr/bin/env zsh
# ONE global queue for heavy Rust builds / test suites / benchmarks.
#
# WHY THIS EXISTS
#   Several agents working in parallel each want to run a full test suite.
#   On a 10-core / 16 GB box those runs do not overlap usefully -- they
#   thrash. CPU oversubscription makes every suite slower than if it had run
#   alone, and memory is the real cliff: a single 1 GB bench here peaks near
#   7.5 GB RSS, so two heavy jobs at once means swap, and swap means suites
#   that never finish.
#
#   MEASURED 2026-07-20 on parot-core (2,269 tests): one `cargo nextest run`
#   consumed 2,930s of CPU against 323s of wall clock -- ~9x parallelism on
#   10 cores. A single suite ALREADY saturates the machine.
#
#   This is a thin wrapper over task-spooler (`ts`), which is a real job queue
#   daemon -- FIFO ordering, weighted admission, job listing, output capture.
#   The wrapper pins ONE global socket (so every agent in every repo shares the
#   same queue), sets the unit budget, keeps the job record `ts` does not, and
#   makes the whole thing a transparent command prefix.
#
# RELATIONSHIP TO cargo-slot -- THEY SOLVE OPPOSITE PROBLEMS, DON'T COMBINE
#   cargo-slot gives each agent its OWN target dir so agents can compile
#   CONCURRENTLY (cargo takes an exclusive lock on target/).
#   testq decides WHICH jobs may overlap at all.
#   Under testq, agents should SHARE one warm target/ per worktree. Use
#   cargo-slot only when you want two builds of the SAME worktree at once.
#
# USAGE
#   testq <command...>             wait for capacity, then run <command> here
#   testq --priority <cmd...>      same, but jump the queue
#   testq --events <cmd...>        emit machine-readable state lines
#   testq -l | --list              show the queue (waiting / running / finished)
#   testq --watch                  live-refreshing queue view
#   testq --status [id|--last]     show the full job record (exit code, timings)
#   testq --exit-code [id|--last]  print just that job's exit code
#   testq --explain <cmd...>       show how a command would be weighted
#   testq --ahead                  how many jobs a new submission waits for
#   testq --budget [N]             show, or set, the concurrency budget
#   testq --clear                  forget finished jobs
#   testq --kill                   stop the queue daemon (not a running job)
#
# EXAMPLES
#   testq cargo nextest run --workspace
#   testq -- cargo build --release        # `--` if the command starts with a flag
#   testq --exit-code --last              # ground truth after piping output
#
# SEMANTICS
#   Blocks until there is capacity, then runs the command IN THIS PROCESS:
#   stdout and stderr stream live and stay separate, the exit code is the
#   command's own, and the job inherits this shell's cwd, stdin and
#   environment. It is a queue, not a sandbox -- `testq X` behaves exactly like
#   `X`, only it waits its turn.
#
#   Because it BLOCKS, a caller with a timeout (an agent's shell tool caps at
#   10 minutes) should run it detached / in the background.
#
# EXIT CODES ARE RECORDED, NOT JUST RETURNED
#   `testq cmd | tail` returns TAIL's status, so a suite with failing tests
#   reads as "exit code 0". That is a shell fact no wrapper can change -- so
#   every job also writes a record, and the code can be read back afterwards:
#
#       testq cargo nextest run --workspace 2>&1 | tail -20
#       testq --exit-code --last            # <- ground truth
#
#   `testq --status --last` shows the whole record: command, cwd, weight,
#   queued/started/finished times and the exit code.
#
# THE CONCURRENCY BUDGET (-N weighting)
#   Jobs declare a cost in UNITS and the queue admits jobs until TESTQ_BUDGET
#   (default 12) is full. A unit is a RELATIVE cost, not a measured quantity of
#   anything -- the numbers were chosen so that the arithmetic enforces the
#   policy, and that is all they mean:
#
#       fmt, doc, metadata        1
#       check, clippy, build      3
#       test, nextest             9
#       bench, miri              12
#
#   The safety property falls out of the arithmetic: one suite plus one check
#   fits (12), two suites never do (18), a bench runs alone. That is the point
#   -- a 20-second `cargo check` no longer waits out a 9-minute suite, which is
#   the worst thing about a flat FIFO.
#
#   The cost, stated plainly: a suite already runs at ~9x parallelism on 10
#   cores (MEASURED 2026-07-20), so a concurrent check does steal cores from it.
#   Trading a few percent of suite wall-clock for a 9-minute-to-30-second drop
#   in check latency is the right trade for work someone is waiting on; it is
#   not free.
#
#   NOT YET MEASURED, and the thing to measure before raising the budget:
#   the peak RSS of a suite and of a concurrent check, together, against the
#   ~13 GB usable. The known figures are the 1 GB bench at ~7.5 GB peak and the
#   suite's 9x CPU parallelism; the suite's own RSS ceiling has not been
#   recorded. Until it is, treat 12 as the maximum, not a starting point.
#
#   Override per-invocation with TESTQ_WEIGHT=<n>. See `testq --explain`.
#
# WHY NOT FAST-PATH AN EMPTY QUEUE
#   "Nothing is running, so just exec directly" is a check-then-act race: two
#   agents both observe an empty queue and both start heavy jobs, unaccounted,
#   which is exactly the collision this exists to prevent. The saving would be
#   a few milliseconds of socket round-trip against jobs measured in minutes.
#   Deliberately not implemented.
#
# HEARTBEAT
#   While waiting, a "still queued" line goes to stderr every TESTQ_HEARTBEAT
#   seconds (default 30; 0 disables). It names the job blocking you and
#   estimates the wait from that command's median runtime. Without it the
#   wrapper goes silent for however long the queue is -- which reads as a hang
#   and provokes callers into re-running the job. TESTQ_QUIET=1 silences it.
#
# --events MODE
#   For callers that want NOTIFICATIONS rather than live output (an agent's
#   Monitor tool turns each stdout line into an event):
#
#     QUEUED id=7 ahead=2 label=tq-1234-… budget=12 weight=9
#     RUNNING id=7 waited=312s
#     DONE id=7 exit=0 elapsed=522s out=/tmp/ts-out.XXXX
#
#   TRADEOFF, on purpose: events mode submits the job DETACHED, so the
#   command's own output is captured to `out=` instead of streaming live. You
#   get notifications or you get streaming, not both.
#
# RE-ENTRANCY
#   A queued job runs with TESTQ_ACTIVE=1. If testq sees that set it runs the
#   command directly instead of enqueuing it. Without this, a queued `just
#   test` whose recipe itself calls testq would wait forever for the capacity
#   its own parent is holding -- a guaranteed self-deadlock.

emulate -L zsh
# no_multios matters: with zsh's default MULTIOS, `2>&1 1>&3` does not move a
# stream, it TEES it, so the capture path below would silently copy stdout into
# the stderr file and a caller's `2>/dev/null` would start eating real output.
setopt no_unset pipe_fail no_multios

readonly SELF="${0:t}"

die() { print -u2 "$SELF: $*"; exit 1 }

# --- already inside a queued job: run directly, never re-enqueue -------------
# Management subcommands still work in here; only an actual command bypasses
# the queue. `--` must be handled explicitly, else `testq -- cargo x` would
# look like a flag, fall through, and deadlock on its parent's capacity.
if [[ -n "${TESTQ_ACTIVE:-}" ]]; then
  case "${1:-}" in
    -h|--help|-l|--list|status|--watch|--slots|--budget|--clear|--kill) ;;
    --status|--exit-code|--explain|--ahead|--ahead-of|"") ;;
    --events|--priority) shift; [[ $# -gt 0 ]] && exec "$@" ;;
    --) shift; [[ $# -gt 0 ]] && exec "$@" ;;
    *)  exec "$@" ;;
  esac
fi

command -v ts >/dev/null 2>&1 || die "task-spooler is not installed -- run: brew install task-spooler"

# ── state layer ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# `ts` tracks a job list; it does not track cwd, target dir, submitter, weight
# class or exit history. Everything built on top -- the exit-code ground truth,
# the ETA, abandon reaping, anti-affinity -- needs those, so testq keeps its own
# record beside the queue.
#
# Records are APPEND-ONLY `key=value` lines and readers take the LAST value for
# a key. Two writers (this process and its background supervisor) can therefore
# both update one record with no locking and no lost updates.
readonly STATE="${TESTQ_STATE:-${XDG_CACHE_HOME:-$HOME/.cache}/testq}"
readonly JOBS="$STATE/jobs"
readonly BY_ID="$STATE/by-id"
readonly LASTD="$STATE/last"
readonly HISTORY="$STATE/history.tsv"

state_init() { mkdir -p "$JOBS" "$BY_ID" "$LASTD" 2>/dev/null || true }

# One record (plus captured output) per job, forever, would quietly turn into
# thousands of files and an unbounded history. Prune on submission, at most
# once a day, so the cost never lands on an interactive `--status`.
prune_state() {
  local stamp="$STATE/.pruned"
  [[ -f "$stamp" && -z "$(find "$stamp" -mtime +1 2>/dev/null)" ]] && return 0
  : >"$stamp"
  find "$JOBS" "$BY_ID" -type f -mtime +7 -delete 2>/dev/null
  if [[ -r "$HISTORY" ]] && (( $(wc -l <"$HISTORY") > 5000 )); then
    tail -n 2000 "$HISTORY" >"$HISTORY.new" 2>/dev/null && mv "$HISTORY.new" "$HISTORY"
  fi
  return 0
}

# Exact whole-line membership. Substring matching would be wrong in both places
# this is used: /repo/target substring-matches /repo/target2, and one session id
# can be a prefix of another -- either would silently mis-schedule.
contains_line() { print -r -- "$1" | grep -qxF -- "$2" }

# Who submitted this. `--last` means "the job *I* just ran", so this key has to
# survive the very shape the feature exists for: `testq cmd | tail` puts testq
# in a subshell, so $PPID is that subshell -- gone by the time you ask for the
# exit code. In order of reliability:
#   1. TESTQ_SESSION -- injected by the PreToolUse hook, stable across an
#      agent's tool calls, and the only key that distinguishes concurrent agents.
#   2. the controlling tty -- stable for a human, across pipelines and subshells.
#   3. the process group -- stable across pipelines in non-interactive shells.
#   4. $PPID -- last resort.
compute_session() {
  [[ -n "${TESTQ_SESSION:-}" ]] && { print -r -- "$TESTQ_SESSION"; return }
  local t g
  t=$(ps -o tty= -p $$ 2>/dev/null | tr -d ' ')
  [[ -n "$t" && "$t" != "??" && "$t" != "?" ]] && { print -r -- "tty-${t//\//-}"; return }
  g=$(ps -o pgid= -p $$ 2>/dev/null | tr -d ' ')
  [[ -n "$g" && "$g" != 0 ]] && { print -r -- "pgid-$g"; return }
  print -r -- "shell-$PPID"
}
readonly SESSION="$(compute_session)"
session_id() { print -r -- "$SESSION" }

rec_put() { print -r -- "$2=$3" >>"$1" 2>/dev/null || true }

# Last value wins, so a later append supersedes an earlier one. A value may
# itself contain '=', hence the substr rather than a field split.
rec_get() {
  [[ -r "$1" ]] || return 1
  local v
  v=$(awk -v k="$2" 'index($0, k "=")==1 {v=substr($0, length(k)+2); f=1} END{if(f) print v}' "$1")
  [[ -n "$v" ]] || return 1
  print -r -- "$v"
}

# A job id -> its record path. Also accepts a label, and `--last` (the most
# recent submission from THIS session, so concurrent agents never read each
# other's job by accident).
rec_path() {
  local ref="${1:-}"
  [[ "$ref" == "--last" || -z "$ref" ]] && ref="$(cat "$LASTD/$(session_id)" 2>/dev/null || true)"
  [[ -n "$ref" ]] || return 1
  [[ -f "$BY_ID/$ref" ]] && { print -r -- "$JOBS/$(cat "$BY_ID/$ref")"; return 0 }
  [[ -f "$JOBS/$ref" ]] && { print -r -- "$JOBS/$ref"; return 0 }
  return 1
}

# ONE socket for the whole machine, independent of cwd, project or shell.
# That single fact is what makes the queue global across agents and repos.
export TS_SOCKET="${TESTQ_SOCKET:-/tmp/testq-${UID}.sock}"
export TS_MAXFINISHED="${TESTQ_MAXFINISHED:-50}"

# TESTQ_SLOTS was a flat job count; TESTQ_BUDGET is a unit budget. Reading an
# old slot count AS a budget would silently make every job exclusive again -- a
# nextest weighs 9, so a budget of 2 clamps it to 2 and nothing ever overlaps,
# which is exactly the head-of-line blocking this version removes. So it is
# ignored, loudly, rather than misinterpreted quietly.
if [[ -z "${TESTQ_BUDGET:-}" && -n "${TESTQ_SLOTS:-}" ]]; then
  print -u2 "$SELF: TESTQ_SLOTS is obsolete and was IGNORED (it counted jobs; the budget counts units). Using the default 12. Set TESTQ_BUDGET in ~/.zshenv."
fi
readonly BUDGET="${TESTQ_BUDGET:-12}"
readonly HEARTBEAT="${TESTQ_HEARTBEAT:-30}"
readonly QUIET="${TESTQ_QUIET:-}"

# `ts -S` starts the daemon if it isn't up, and pins the budget if it is.
# Both are idempotent, so this is safe to call on every invocation.
ensure_server() {
  ts -S "$BUDGET" >/dev/null 2>&1 \
    || die "could not start or reach the queue daemon at $TS_SOCKET"
}

# ── queue introspection ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# `ts -l` is a header line plus one line per job; state is the second column.
# Everything here parses by COLUMN, never by searching the command text, so a
# job whose command happens to contain the word "running" cannot skew a count.

# How many jobs will consume capacity before a NEW submission does.
queue_depth() {
  ts -l 2>/dev/null | tail -n +2 |
    awk '$2=="queued" || $2=="running" {n++} END{print n+0}'
}

# Jobs strictly AHEAD of job $1 in run order.
#
# THE BUG THIS REPLACES: the old version counted every unfinished job except
# your own, so a job submitted BEHIND you also incremented your count. The
# number grew as the queue grew, which reads as losing ground and makes a
# bounded wait feel unbounded. Run order is job-id order, so only lower ids can
# be ahead of us.
queue_ahead_of() {
  ts -l 2>/dev/null | tail -n +2 |
    awk -v me="$1" '($2=="queued" || $2=="running") && ($1+0) < (me+0) {n++} END{print n+0}'
}

ids_in_state() {
  ts -l 2>/dev/null | tail -n +2 | awk -v s="$1" '$2==s {print $1}'
}

state_of_id() { ts -s "$1" 2>/dev/null || true }

# Empty means "not enqueued yet" -- NOT "gone". A caller must not treat the two
# as the same or it will stop watching before the job ever appears.
id_by_label() {
  ts -l 2>/dev/null | tail -n +2 | awk -v l="[$1]" 'index($0, l) {print $1; exit}'
}

# ── weight classification ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Units are a relative cost scale, not measured GB; see the header for the table
# and the tradeoff. `cargo +nightly test` puts the toolchain first, so a leading
# `+` is skipped. Prints "<class> <weight>".
classify() {
  local -a w=("$@")
  local i base sub
  for (( i = 1; i <= $#w; i++ )); do
    base="${w[i]:t}"
    sub="${w[i+1]:-}"
    [[ "$sub" == +* ]] && sub="${w[i+2]:-}"
    case "$base" in
      cargo)
        case "$sub" in
          bench|miri)   print -- "$sub 12"; return ;;
          test|nextest) print -- "$sub 9";  return ;;
          build|check|clippy|doc|install|rustc)
                        print -- "$sub 3";  return ;;
        esac
        print -- "cargo-light 1"; return ;;
      just)
        case "$sub" in
          bench*) print -- "just-bench 12"; return ;;
          test*)  print -- "just-test 9";   return ;;
          lint*)  print -- "just-lint 3";   return ;;
        esac
        print -- "just-light 1"; return ;;
    esac
  done
  print -- "other 1"
}

# ── duration history ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Every completion appends one row, so the queue can answer "is this worth
# waiting for" rather than just "please wait".
history_append() {
  print -r -- "$1\t$2\t$3\t$4" >>"$HISTORY" 2>/dev/null || true
}

# Median duration for a command key, falling back to its weight class. Absent
# history returns FAILURE -- callers must render that as "unknown", never as 0,
# or a first-ever job would advertise an ETA of zero seconds.
history_median() {
  local class="$1" cmdkey="${2:-}" vals
  [[ -r "$HISTORY" ]] || return 1
  vals=$(awk -F'\t' -v k="$cmdkey" '$2==k {print $3}' "$HISTORY" 2>/dev/null)
  [[ -n "$vals" ]] || vals=$(awk -F'\t' -v c="$class" '$1==c {print $3}' "$HISTORY" 2>/dev/null)
  [[ -n "$vals" ]] || return 1
  print -r -- "$vals" | sort -n | awk '{a[NR]=$1} END{print a[int((NR+1)/2)]}'
}

# A stable identity for "the same command in the same place", used to look up
# how long this kind of job usually takes.
cmd_key() { print -r -- "$PWD $*" | shasum | cut -c1-12 }

# Where cargo will take its exclusive artifact lock. Two jobs sharing this
# cannot really compile at once whatever the queue says.
target_dir_of() {
  [[ -n "${CARGO_TARGET_DIR:-}" ]] && { print -r -- "$CARGO_TARGET_DIR"; return }
  local root
  root=$(git rev-parse --show-toplevel 2>/dev/null) || root="$PWD"
  print -r -- "$root/target"
}

# ── abandon reaping ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# An agent's shell tool SIGKILLs its process group on timeout, so no trap fires
# and the queued job outlives its submitter -- it eventually runs, for nobody,
# holding capacity someone else could use. Every submission sweeps for those.
#
# A job with no record predates this version or came from elsewhere: leave it
# alone. Reaping something we cannot identify is worse than leaving it.
reap_abandoned() {
  local id recfile pid
  for id in ${(f)"$(ids_in_state queued)"}; do
    recfile=$(rec_path "$id" 2>/dev/null) || continue
    pid=$(rec_get "$recfile" pid) || continue
    kill -0 "$pid" 2>/dev/null && continue
    ts -r "$id" >/dev/null 2>&1 && rec_put "$recfile" reaped "$(date +%s)"
  done
}

# ── deduplication of concurrent identical work ───────────────────────────────
# When N agents verify the same branch, several submit a byte-identical command
# against an unchanged tree. Only the first needs to run; the rest can watch.
#
# WHAT "IDENTICAL" HAS TO MEAN, given that returning a stale result the caller
# cannot distinguish from a fresh one is the worst thing this tool could do:
# same cwd, same argv, same HEAD, same dirty-file fingerprint, same build-shaping
# environment. All of that goes INTO the key, so a tree that has moved simply
# produces a different key and coalesces with nothing -- there is no separate
# "is it still valid" check to get wrong.
#
# THE CONTRACT, precisely: a follower gets the result of a run of this exact
# command against this exact tree state, started at the moment its own run would
# have started. Coalescing only ever happens with a leader that is still
# running -- the leader removes its claim the instant it finishes, so this is a
# concurrency optimisation, never a result cache that can serve yesterday's
# answer.
#
# NOT ELIGIBLE, deliberately: interactive (tty) callers, which keep the fully
# transparent path; anything outside a git repo, since without a fingerprint
# there is no way to know the tree is unchanged and guessing is not an option.
readonly DEDUP="$STATE/dedup"

dedup_eligible() {
  [[ -z "${TESTQ_NO_DEDUP:-}" ]] || return 1
  [[ ! -t 1 ]] || return 1
  git rev-parse --show-toplevel >/dev/null 2>&1
}

# HEAD plus the identity of every dirty/untracked file. Size+mtime rather than
# content: cheap, and it cannot miss an edit, which is the direction that
# matters. An unreadable or enormous working tree returns failure -- and failure
# means "run it for real", never "assume unchanged".
tree_fingerprint() {
  local head files n
  head=$(git rev-parse HEAD 2>/dev/null) || return 1
  files=$(git ls-files -m -o --exclude-standard 2>/dev/null) || return 1
  n=$(print -r -- "$files" | grep -c . || true)
  (( n > 1000 )) && return 1
  # `if`, not `[[ ... ]] &&`: a false `&&` would make the brace group exit
  # non-zero, and under pipe_fail that becomes the whole pipeline's status --
  # so a perfectly CLEAN tree would report "no fingerprint" and silently
  # disable dedup exactly when it is most likely to apply.
  {
    print -r -- "$head"
    if [[ -n "$files" ]]; then
      print -r -- "$files" | while IFS= read -r f; do
        stat -f '%N %m %z' -- "$f" 2>/dev/null || print -r -- "$f UNREADABLE"
      done
    fi
  } | shasum | cut -c1-16
}

# Variables that change what a build PRODUCES. Two runs that differ here are not
# the same job however identical their argv.
dedup_env() {
  local v
  for v in CARGO_TARGET_DIR CARGO_INCREMENTAL RUSTFLAGS RUSTDOCFLAGS \
           RUSTC_WRAPPER RUSTUP_TOOLCHAIN RUST_LOG CARGO_BUILD_JOBS; do
    print -r -- "$v=$(printenv "$v" 2>/dev/null || true)"
  done
}

dedup_key() {
  local fp
  fp=$(tree_fingerprint) || return 1
  {
    print -r -- "$PWD"
    print -r -- "${(j: :)${(q+)@}}"
    print -r -- "$fp"
    dedup_env
  } | shasum | cut -c1-24
}

# Attach to a running leader: stream back exactly what it produced and report
# its code in FOLLOW_RC. Returns 1 if there is nothing safe to attach to, in
# which case the caller runs the job for real.
#
# The result comes back through a global rather than stdout on purpose: this
# function's whole job is to WRITE the leader's output to the real stdout and
# stderr, so it must not be called in a command substitution that would capture
# exactly the bytes it exists to emit.
FOLLOW_RC=0
dedup_follow() {
  local key="$1" leader lrec lpid code
  leader=$(cat "$DEDUP/$key/leader" 2>/dev/null) || return 1
  [[ -n "$leader" ]] || return 1
  lrec="$JOBS/$leader"
  [[ -r "$lrec" ]] || return 1
  lpid=$(rec_get "$lrec" pid) || return 1

  say "identical job already running (${leader}); attaching instead of queueing a duplicate"
  while :; do
    code=$(rec_get "$lrec" exit) && break
    # A leader that died without recording an exit leaves nothing to attach to.
    kill -0 "$lpid" 2>/dev/null || return 1
    sleep 1
  done

  [[ -r "$JOBS/$leader.out" ]] && cat "$JOBS/$leader.out"
  [[ -r "$JOBS/$leader.err" ]] && cat "$JOBS/$leader.err" >&2
  rec_put "$RECORD" deduped_from "$leader"
  rec_put "$RECORD" started  "$(date +%s)"
  rec_put "$RECORD" finished "$(date +%s)"
  rec_put "$RECORD" exit "$code"
  FOLLOW_RC="$code"
}

# ── the waiting message ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# "waiting for a free slot" does not say who holds it, and the decision the
# caller is actually making is "is this worth waiting for". So name the blocker
# and estimate, from its own history, how much longer it has.
describe_blocker() {
  local id recfile cmd cwd started class key med elapsed est desc now
  id=$(ids_in_state running | head -1)
  [[ -n "$id" ]] || return 1
  now=$(date +%s)

  recfile=$(rec_path "$id" 2>/dev/null) || { print -r -- "job $id"; return 0 }
  cmd=$(rec_get "$recfile" cmd)     || cmd="?"
  cwd=$(rec_get "$recfile" cwd)     || cwd=""
  started=$(rec_get "$recfile" started) || started=""
  class=$(rec_get "$recfile" class) || class=""
  key=$(rec_get "$recfile" cmdkey)  || key=""

  desc="job $id (${cwd:t}: ${cmd:0:60}"
  if [[ -n "$started" ]]; then
    elapsed=$(( now - started ))
    desc="$desc, running ${elapsed}s"
  fi
  if med=$(history_median "$class" "$key"); then
    desc="$desc; median ${med}s"
    if [[ -n "$started" ]]; then
      est=$(( med - elapsed ))
      (( est < 0 )) && est=0
    fi
  fi
  desc="$desc)"
  [[ -n "${est:-}" ]] && desc="$desc — est. ${est}s"
  print -r -- "$desc"
}

say() { [[ -n "$QUIET" ]] || print -u2 "$SELF: $*" }

# ── management subcommands ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
case "${1:-}" in
  -h|--help)
    sed -n '/^# USAGE/,/^# RE-ENTRANCY/p' "$0" | sed 's/^# \?//'
    exit 0 ;;
  -l|--list|status)
    ensure_server; exec ts -l ;;
  --watch)
    ensure_server
    while :; do clear; print "queue: $TS_SOCKET  (budget: $BUDGET units)"; print; ts -l; sleep 2; done ;;
  --budget|--slots)
    [[ "$1" == "--slots" ]] && print -u2 "$SELF: --slots is deprecated; it now sets the unit BUDGET (see --help)."
    ensure_server
    if [[ -n "${2:-}" ]]; then
      ts -S "$2" || die "could not set the budget to $2"
      print "$SELF: budget -> $2 units (this session only; export TESTQ_BUDGET=$2 to persist)"
    else
      print "$SELF: budget = $BUDGET units  (socket: $TS_SOCKET)"
    fi
    exit 0 ;;
  --clear)
    ensure_server; exec ts -C ;;
  --kill)
    ts -K 2>/dev/null && print "$SELF: queue daemon stopped" || print "$SELF: no queue daemon running"
    exit 0 ;;
  --explain)
    shift
    [[ $# -gt 0 ]] || die "--explain needs a command"
    read -r cls wt <<<"$(classify "$@")"
    (( wt > BUDGET )) && wt=$BUDGET
    print "class=$cls weight=$wt budget=$BUDGET"
    print "at most $(( BUDGET / wt )) job(s) of this weight run at once"
    exit 0 ;;
  --ahead)
    ensure_server; queue_depth; exit 0 ;;
  --ahead-of)
    [[ -n "${2:-}" ]] || die "--ahead-of needs a job id"
    ensure_server; queue_ahead_of "$2"; exit 0 ;;
  --status)
    state_init
    recfile=$(rec_path "${2:---last}") || die "no job record for '${2:---last}'"
    exec cat "$recfile" ;;
  --exit-code)
    state_init
    recfile=$(rec_path "${2:---last}") || die "no job record for '${2:---last}'"
    code=$(rec_get "$recfile" exit) \
      || die "that job has not finished; no exit code recorded yet"
    print -r -- "$code"
    exit 0 ;;
esac

# ── job submission ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
EVENTS=0
PRIORITY=0
while true; do
  case "${1:-}" in
    --events)   EVENTS=1; shift ;;
    --priority) PRIORITY=1; shift ;;
    *) break ;;
  esac
done
[[ "${1:-}" == "--" ]] && shift
[[ $# -gt 0 ]] || die "nothing to run. See '$SELF --help'."

state_init
prune_state
ensure_server
reap_abandoned

LABEL="tq-$$-${RANDOM}"
read -r CLASS WEIGHT <<<"$(classify "$@")"
[[ -n "${TESTQ_WEIGHT:-}" ]] && WEIGHT="$TESTQ_WEIGHT"
(( WEIGHT > BUDGET )) && WEIGHT=$BUDGET
(( WEIGHT < 1 )) && WEIGHT=1

# An interactive submission is a human waiting at a terminal, and it is the
# most penalised caller in the system today -- background agent suites starve
# the one job someone is actually watching. Give it the priority lane.
[[ -t 1 ]] && PRIORITY=1

RECORD="$JOBS/$LABEL"
CMDKEY="$(cmd_key "$@")"
: >"$RECORD"
rec_put "$RECORD" label      "$LABEL"
rec_put "$RECORD" pid        "$$"
rec_put "$RECORD" session    "$(session_id)"
rec_put "$RECORD" cwd        "$PWD"
rec_put "$RECORD" target_dir "$(target_dir_of)"
rec_put "$RECORD" cmd        "${(j: :)${(q+)@}}"
rec_put "$RECORD" cmdkey     "$CMDKEY"
rec_put "$RECORD" class      "$CLASS"
rec_put "$RECORD" weight     "$WEIGHT"
rec_put "$RECORD" budget     "$BUDGET"
rec_put "$RECORD" priority   "$PRIORITY"
rec_put "$RECORD" submitted  "$(date +%s)"
print -r -- "$LABEL" >"$LASTD/$(session_id)" 2>/dev/null || true

# --- events mode: detached submission, one line per state transition ---------
if (( EVENTS )); then
  id="$(TESTQ_ACTIVE=1 ts -L "$LABEL" -N "$WEIGHT" "$@")" \
    || die "could not enqueue job"
  rec_put "$RECORD" id "$id"
  print -r -- "$LABEL" >"$BY_ID/$id" 2>/dev/null || true
  (( PRIORITY )) && ts -u "$id" >/dev/null 2>&1
  print "QUEUED id=$id ahead=$(queue_ahead_of "$id") label=$LABEL budget=$BUDGET weight=$WEIGHT"
  t0=$(date +%s)
  while [[ "$(state_of_id "$id")" == "queued" ]]; do sleep 1; done
  rec_put "$RECORD" started "$(date +%s)"
  print "RUNNING id=$id waited=$(( $(date +%s) - t0 ))s"
  t1=$(date +%s)
  ts -w "$id" >/dev/null 2>&1
  rc=$?
  el=$(( $(date +%s) - t1 ))
  rec_put "$RECORD" finished "$(date +%s)"
  rec_put "$RECORD" exit "$rc"
  rec_put "$RECORD" out "$(ts -o "$id" 2>/dev/null || true)"
  history_append "$CLASS" "$CMDKEY" "$el" "$rc"
  print "DONE id=$id exit=$rc elapsed=${el}s out=$(ts -o "$id" 2>/dev/null)"
  exit $rc
fi

# --- coalesce with an identical in-flight job, if there is one ---------------
# The claim is a directory, because mkdir is atomic: exactly one of N racing
# submitters can create it, and that one is the leader. No lock file, no window.
CAPTURE=0
DEDUP_KEY=""
if dedup_eligible && DEDUP_KEY=$(dedup_key "$@"); then
  mkdir -p "$DEDUP" 2>/dev/null || true
  if mkdir "$DEDUP/$DEDUP_KEY" 2>/dev/null; then
    print -r -- "$LABEL" >"$DEDUP/$DEDUP_KEY/leader" 2>/dev/null || true
    CAPTURE=1
  elif dedup_follow "$DEDUP_KEY"; then
    exit "$FOLLOW_RC"
  else
    # A claim with nothing usable behind it -- the leader was SIGKILLed before
    # recording anything. Take it over rather than wait on a ghost forever.
    print -r -- "$LABEL" >"$DEDUP/$DEDUP_KEY/leader" 2>/dev/null || true
    CAPTURE=1
  fi
fi

# --- normal mode: transparent, with a supervisor while we wait ---------------
#
# `ts -nf` blocks and never reveals the job id, so a background supervisor
# discovers it by label and owns everything needing that id: the record, the
# priority bump, anti-affinity promotion and the heartbeat. The parent stays a
# plain blocking call, which is what keeps the wrapper transparent.
AHEAD_AT_SUBMIT=$(queue_depth)
if (( AHEAD_AT_SUBMIT > 0 )); then
  say "$AHEAD_AT_SUBMIT job(s) ahead; blocked by $(describe_blocker || print -r -- 'a running job') (budget: $BUDGET units, this job: $WEIGHT)"
fi

supervise() {
  local id="" waited=0 t0=$SECONDS promoted=0 tries=0 st last_ahead=999999

  # Discover our id. Polling fast matters: a priority bump only helps if it
  # lands before the scheduler picks the next job.
  while (( tries < 400 )); do
    id=$(id_by_label "$LABEL")
    [[ -n "$id" ]] && break
    sleep 0.05
    (( tries++ ))
  done
  [[ -n "$id" ]] || return 0

  rec_put "$RECORD" id "$id"
  print -r -- "$LABEL" >"$BY_ID/$id" 2>/dev/null || true
  (( PRIORITY )) && ts -u "$id" >/dev/null 2>&1

  while :; do
    st=$(state_of_id "$id")
    [[ "$st" == "running" || "$st" == "finished" || -z "$st" ]] && break

    if (( ! promoted )) && { promote_if_unblocked "$id" || promote_if_starved "$id" }; then
      promoted=1
    fi

    if (( HEARTBEAT > 0 )) && (( SECONDS - t0 >= HEARTBEAT )); then
      t0=$SECONDS
      local ahead
      ahead=$(queue_ahead_of "$id")
      # A position that grows reads as losing ground; it is also never true,
      # since only lower ids count. Clamp anyway so a daemon restart or an
      # id-reuse edge case can't make the number climb.
      (( ahead > last_ahead )) && ahead=$last_ahead
      last_ahead=$ahead
      say "still queued — ${waited}s elapsed, $ahead ahead; blocked by $(describe_blocker || print -r -- 'a running job')"
    fi
    sleep 1
    (( waited++ ))
  done
  rec_put "$RECORD" started "$(date +%s)"
}

# ANTI-AFFINITY. Cargo takes an exclusive lock on target/, so two jobs sharing
# a target dir cannot really compile at once no matter what the queue allows --
# the second one just sits on "Blocking waiting for file lock", burning
# capacity for nothing.
#
# (This is the inverse of the "batch by worktree" idea it replaces. That one
# assumed alternating worktrees loses a warm target dir, which is false here:
# there is no global CARGO_TARGET_DIR, so every worktree keeps its own.)
#
# So: if every job ahead of us wants a target dir that is already locked by a
# running job, and ours is free, we can start now and nobody starts later.
# Promotion happens at most once per job, so it cannot starve the queue.
promote_if_unblocked() {
  local id="$1" mine running_dirs="" other op qp qdir
  mine=$(rec_get "$RECORD" target_dir) || return 1

  for other in ${(f)"$(ids_in_state running)"}; do
    op=$(rec_path "$other" 2>/dev/null) || return 1   # unknown job: don't guess
    running_dirs+="$(rec_get "$op" target_dir || true)"$'\n'
  done
  [[ -n "$running_dirs" ]] || return 1
  contains_line "$running_dirs" "$mine" && return 1   # we'd contend too

  for other in ${(f)"$(ids_in_state queued)"}; do
    (( other >= id )) && continue
    qp=$(rec_path "$other" 2>/dev/null) || return 1
    qdir=$(rec_get "$qp" target_dir) || return 1
    contains_line "$running_dirs" "$qdir" || return 1 # that one isn't blocked
  done

  ts -u "$id" >/dev/null 2>&1
}

# FAIR SHARE ACROSS SESSIONS. Pure FIFO lets one session's fan-out flood the
# queue: ten agents from one session submit ten suites, and another session's
# single job waits behind all ten. If our session has nothing running, and every
# job ahead of us belongs to a session that is ALREADY being served, we can go
# first without delaying anyone who isn't already getting their turn.
#
# Like the anti-affinity bump this fires at most once per job, so it reorders
# the queue a little and cannot livelock it.
promote_if_starved() {
  local id="$1" mine other op osess running_sessions=""
  mine=$(rec_get "$RECORD" session) || return 1

  for other in ${(f)"$(ids_in_state running)"}; do
    op=$(rec_path "$other" 2>/dev/null) || return 1   # unknown job: don't guess
    running_sessions+="$(rec_get "$op" session || true)"$'\n'
  done
  [[ -n "$running_sessions" ]] || return 1
  contains_line "$running_sessions" "$mine" && return 1

  for other in ${(f)"$(ids_in_state queued)"}; do
    (( other >= id )) && continue
    op=$(rec_path "$other" 2>/dev/null) || return 1
    osess=$(rec_get "$op" session) || return 1
    contains_line "$running_sessions" "$osess" || return 1
  done

  ts -u "$id" >/dev/null 2>&1
}

supervise &
SUP_PID=$!

# A queued job that outlives its submitter runs for nobody. The trap covers a
# clean kill; reap_abandoned covers SIGKILL, where no trap can fire.
cleanup() {
  (( SUP_PID > 0 )) && kill "$SUP_PID" 2>/dev/null
  [[ -n "$DEDUP_KEY" ]] && rm -rf "$DEDUP/$DEDUP_KEY" 2>/dev/null
  local id
  id=$(rec_get "$RECORD" id 2>/dev/null) || return 0
  [[ "$(state_of_id "$id")" == "queued" ]] && ts -r "$id" >/dev/null 2>&1
  return 0
}
trap cleanup INT TERM

T_START=$(date +%s)
# -n : inherit this process's stdout/stderr instead of capturing to a file
# -f : don't detach -- wait for capacity, then run right here
# Together they make the wrapper transparent: live output on the right streams,
# the real exit code, the caller's cwd, stdin and environment.
if (( CAPTURE )); then
  # A leader has to keep a copy for its followers. Both tees are members of a
  # real pipeline, so the shell waits for them -- the files are complete by the
  # time this returns, which a background `tee &` could not guarantee. The exit
  # code travels out of band through a file, since the pipeline's own status
  # belongs to tee. Streams stay separate; only their tty-ness is lost, and
  # capture is off for tty callers precisely so that never matters.
  rm -f "$JOBS/$LABEL.out" "$JOBS/$LABEL.err" "$JOBS/$LABEL.rc" 2>/dev/null
  {
    { TESTQ_ACTIVE=1 ts -nf -L "$LABEL" -N "$WEIGHT" "$@"
      print -r -- $? >"$JOBS/$LABEL.rc"
    } 2>&1 1>&3 | tee "$JOBS/$LABEL.err" >&2
  } 3>&1 | tee "$JOBS/$LABEL.out"
  rc=$(cat "$JOBS/$LABEL.rc" 2>/dev/null) || rc=1
  rec_put "$RECORD" out "$JOBS/$LABEL.out"
  rec_put "$RECORD" err "$JOBS/$LABEL.err"
else
  TESTQ_ACTIVE=1 ts -nf -L "$LABEL" -N "$WEIGHT" "$@"
  rc=$?
fi
(( SUP_PID > 0 )) && kill "$SUP_PID" 2>/dev/null
trap - INT TERM

# Release the claim before recording the exit code, so that "a follower only
# ever attaches to a leader that is still running" stays literally true.
[[ -n "$DEDUP_KEY" ]] && rm -rf "$DEDUP/$DEDUP_KEY" 2>/dev/null

T_END=$(date +%s)

# Backfill what the supervisor may not have had time to write. A job that
# starts immediately can finish before the supervisor has even found its id, so
# without this a short job would have no `id=` and no by-id index -- and then
# `testq --status <id>` would report "no job record" for a job that plainly ran.
if ! ID=$(rec_get "$RECORD" id); then
  ID=$(id_by_label "$LABEL")
  [[ -n "$ID" ]] && {
    rec_put "$RECORD" id "$ID"
    print -r -- "$LABEL" >"$BY_ID/$ID" 2>/dev/null || true
  }
fi

rec_put "$RECORD" finished "$T_END"
rec_put "$RECORD" exit "$rc"
STARTED=$(rec_get "$RECORD" started) || { STARTED=$T_START; rec_put "$RECORD" started "$T_START" }
history_append "$CLASS" "$CMDKEY" "$(( T_END - STARTED ))" "$rc"

exit $rc
